node.text: A chat about Momo’s cognitive dysfunction syndrome and overall CDS. It affects over a third of dogs and catching the signs early can mean seriously improving your dogs senior health. I’m hoping this video helps educate a bit. A big thanks to @drlisalippman for educating us, as always!

node.text:
Me looking through the 500,000 photos of Momo I’ve taken: damn wish I’d taken more photos

I can’t recall a time I’ve been more present than the moments before Momo left this earth. Like I was throwing down a temporal anchor so I can always go back. It worked - I can still feel the wind, hear the birds, see the river, and feel the moment I took my shoes off so I can feel the earth like he did. I can still be there with him. I suppose that’s one purpose of emotion – to anchor ourselves in events that matter.

That’s me, a rational man, looking for logic in emotion so I can integrate it better into my life.

I like to think that Boo’s heartbeat became synchronized with Momo’s and still follows the same pulse.

I’ve been trying to spend more time outside, that helps. August was mostly printing and shipping photos and stickers and watching AP Bio and White Lotus and Reservation Dogs.

I’ve gotta thank you again for your support. Printing those photos one at a time, stamping them, and spending time with them was a cathartic exercise and truly mended some things. Your support lifted me up and carried me, so, thank you.

node.text:
I picked up my medium format for the first time in a while and captured this frame. A part of me wanted to stop taking pictures, I guess as a protest. I felt guilty, like I shouldn’t be taking photos if Momo isn’t around. But another part of me countered. Maybe taking pictures connects me to the world around me, maybe this isn’t a shameful thing, this is something that makes me whole, he taught me how to use a camera, this is how I honour him.

All of these little acts of honour continue to occur. I’m asking myself “would Momo want this for me?”. The question beneath the question is “is this what I want for myself?”. There’s honour in loss. Of course there’s pain and wallowing and anger and dragging one’s feet, we get a free pass for most of these. But if Momo were here, which he is, he’d want health, he’d want life, he’d want me to run for the ball with him full speed laughing.

I know a lot of you have experienced loss like mine. I’m curious about the ways it made you better. Did you notice this?

node.text:
This is a big thank you.

Thank you to everyone who sent their love in any way from a single emoji to sharing your story to keeping us in your thoughts. I received countless stories of your dogs, your families, your lives that touched me deeply. I haven’t been able to read them all though I’ve been trying, and I’m sorry if I didn’t respond. Thank you for the hugs that I’m more grateful for now than ever. Thank you to everyone who’s decided to support me on Patreon and beyond, your support gives me a little more faith in myself and helps weaken the foundation of my imposter syndrome. Thank you to everyone who kept the mood light and gave me something to laugh about in these past few weeks. Thank you to everyone that was there in person or not, to everyone who’s shared a moment with Momo, to everyone who has supported my work and helped shape my life.

I often think of this thing Brian Eno said when he came across an ornate chest of drawers: “If I followed the message of this little set of drawers, and built everything else around that, that would be a different life.” I’m thinking about how I followed the message that I perceived in Momo – the unconditional love, the steadfast spirit – I followed this message for my 13 years with Momo and this gave me direction and shaped my life indefinitely. I take solace knowing that, intentionally or not, I will continue to celebrate this message.

I’m trying to shift this “oh man this sucks” grief phase into a “oh man what an amazing dog” celebratory phase because I’d rather shout about how damn good a dog he was than drag my feet around indefinitely. Of course, it’s OK to drag your feet around too.

I’m going to sell some prints as soon as I can collect myself.

📸 @julianvictoria0

Boo, my eternal optimist. I think he understands what happened. That Momo isn’t here anymore. Though I do catch him looking around once in a while like he’s not sure what he’s looking for but he knows something’s missing.

Boo’s spot that looks like Momo is still there. I couldn’t see it for a while and lately it’s reappeared. See the second photo (which I’ve enhanced a bit for the skeptics).

I shared a lot about grief in my newsletter this morning. I hope my thoughts weren’t too scattered, that’s just how I’ve been feeling I guess. Let me know what you thought. (If you missed it, you can sign up at the link in my profile and I’ll send it out to new subscribers).

Grief is both soft and hard. It stops my heart when I least expect it and just as often gives me gratitude for what Momo was and still is. I know grief isn’t a really popular topic (autocorrect keeps changing grief to fried like I’m more likely to talk about that), but I’ve been writing a bit about my ongoing experience, as it’s been helping me manage my own. I’m going to put some thoughts together for my newsletter on Monday incase anyone is interested.

I’d like to hear about your experience with grief, be it anticipatory, coping mechanisms, quotes/ideas that have helped you put things into perspective, or things you didn’t expect. Or just a characteristic you miss/cherish that gets stirred up thinking about someone or somepet you love and/or lost. 

Thanks to @zachdriftwood for capturing this photo of Momo and I a few weeks ago.

node.text:
Yesterday was a powerful transition, a paradigm shift in my life. There’s an imposing emptiness in my throat, like a reverse nostalgia. I know it’s only there because of the fullness that Momo offered, because of how much he lived and allowed me to experience life.

Momo was pure love. Even in his final days his eyes lit up my life. He was loyal, he was patient as a statue and I could swear he spoke English. 

I’m thankful for all the praise and messages you’ve been sending. Martin Prechtel describes grief and praise as the same thing. “Grief is praise, because it is the natural way love honors what it misses.” Praise for someone that’s gone isn’t praise for the dead, it’s praise for the fact that they were alive. And this dog was alive enough that I grieved him before he was gone, and I’ll praise him until my end.

Nature praised him too, yesterday. The clouds cried all night and the sky opened up an hour before the ceremony. His final breath was at 12:43, and my heart went quiet. I shared quietude and laughter with some close friends and their kids. In the evening, the sky grieved red. And fireflies outnumbered my tears in the most impressive twilight display I’ve seen. 

I still can’t believe he’s gone. But when someone asks “why can’t dogs live forever?”, I’m always tempted to respond, “they do”.

node.text:
Today, Momo will be taking his last road trip. We’re driving to a friend’s farm near Ottawa where tomorrow morning, I’ll celebrate his life with some close friends and let him pass on from this earthly plane. With a few phone calls I was able to find a reputable and compassionate in-home end-of-life care provider. 

His struggles have become unjustifiable and irreversible. His quality of life is no longer there, and I had to make the best decision for him. It’s the single hardest choice I’ve ever had to make. These past few days have been full of tears and shared stories.

Have him in your heart. You’ve been there with us for his whole journey, and I want you here with us through this next, most difficult chapter.

I can’t begin to express how much this dog has impacted my life, and countless others. I’m a wreck, but grateful to be able to process this with him by my side. I’m especially grateful for the ongoing love and support you’ve offered us. 

With love and gratitude,

Andrew
